@*
    Delete confirmation view.
    Always show a confirmation step before deleting data — never delete on a GET request.

    WHY? If delete were a GET (/Books/Delete/3), a malicious link in an email or webpage
    could trick a logged-in user's browser into deleting data without them knowing.
    Using POST + antiforgery token prevents this (CSRF protection).

    Flow:
      GET  /Books/Delete/3  → Shows this confirmation page
      POST /Books/DeleteConfirmed → Actually deletes and redirects to Index
*@
@model CetStudentBook.Models.Book

@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Delete Book";
}

<h1 class="text-danger">Delete Book</h1>
<hr />

<div class="alert alert-warning">
    <strong>Are you sure you want to delete this book?</strong>
    This action cannot be undone.
</div>

@*
    We show the book details so the user can confirm they're deleting the right one.
*@
<div class="card mb-4" style="max-width: 500px;">
    <div class="card-header bg-danger text-white">
        Book to be deleted
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
        <dl class="row mb-0">
            <dt class="col-sm-4">Name</dt>
            <dd class="col-sm-8">@Model.Name</dd>

            <dt class="col-sm-4">Author</dt>
            <dd class="col-sm-8">@Model.Author</dd>

            <dt class="col-sm-4">Publish Date</dt>
            <dd class="col-sm-8">@Model.PublishDate.ToString("dd MMM yyyy")</dd>

            <dt class="col-sm-4">Page Count</dt>
            <dd class="col-sm-8">@Model.PageCount</dd>

            <dt class="col-sm-4">Second Hand</dt>
            <dd class="col-sm-8">@(Model.IsSecondHand ? "Yes" : "No")</dd>
        </dl>
    </div>
</div>

@*
    The form posts to the "DeleteConfirmed" action.
    We pass the Id in a hidden field — the controller needs it to find and remove the record.

    Why a separate action name "DeleteConfirmed"?
    Because both GET and POST would go to "Delete" otherwise.
    ASP.NET MVC doesn't allow two methods with the same name and same parameters,
    so we rename the POST version to "DeleteConfirmed".
    (Some developers use [ActionName("Delete")] attribute instead — same result.)
*@
<form asp-action="DeleteConfirmed" method="post">
    <input type="hidden" asp-for="Id" />
    <div class="d-flex gap-2">
        <button type="submit" class="btn btn-danger">Yes, Delete It</button>
        <a asp-action="Index" class="btn btn-secondary">No, Go Back</a>
    </div>
</form>
